					<div class="comment-content">
						<p>Hi Richard,</p>
<p>/ The use of the &#8220;this&#8221; object inside the setTimeout function refers to the Window object, not to myObj​<br />
​<br />
​var highValue = 200;<br />
​var constantVal = 2;<br />
​var myObj = {<br />
	highValue: 20,<br />
	constantVal: 5,<br />
	calculateIt: function () {<br />
 setTimeout (function  () {<br />
	console.log(this.constantVal * this.highValue);<br />
}, 2000);<br />
	}<br />
}<br />
​<br />
​// The &#8220;this&#8221; object in the setTimeout function used the global highValue and constantVal variables, because the reference to &#8220;this&#8221; in the setTimeout function refers to the global window object, not to the myObj object as we might expect.​</p>
<p>myObj.calculateIt(); // 400​<br />
​// This is an important point to remember.</p>
<p>WHY &#8220;this&#8221; IN THE SETTIMEOUT FUNCTION REFERS TO THE GLOBAL WINDOW OBJECT.<br />
As in your expalanation about &#8220;this&#8221;  , you mentioned the calling object properties will be manipulated.<br />
How is it different here ?????????</p>
						
											</div>

